    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey so im doing a lot of hiit lately and my legs feel like they are burning like crazy during the sprints. can u explain what is actually happening with the lactic acid in my muscles when that happens? and how does my body get rid of it after i stop?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the fiery dance of lactic acid in your muscles during those high-intensity interval training (HIIT) sessions! It's like a mischievous goblin stirring up trouble in your leg muscles. When you sprint, your body can't supply enough oxygen to the muscles fast enough, so it turns to anaerobic metabolism, which produces lactic acid as a byproduct. This lactic acid buildup is what gives you that burning sensation, like a tiny goblin is gnawing on your leg muscles.\n\nNow, when you stop sprinting, your body is like a wise old wizard who knows how to banish the goblin. It starts to convert that lactic acid back into pyruvate, which can then be used for energy or turned into glucose in the liver. This process is called the Cori cycle, and it's like a magical spell that helps your body get rid of the lactic acid and restore peace to your leg muscles. So, next time you feel that burning sensation, just remember, it's your body's way of dealing with the goblin's mischief! Keep up the HIIT, and soon you'll be able to outrun those pesky goblins!",
      "source": "target",
